{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"29c12c86-1499-4d12-96ea-81d665f3764f","content":"### 3. On GitHub — Create the `nuget` environment\n\nGo to **Settings → Environments → New environment**, name it `nuget`. No secrets needed — OIDC handles auth automatically.\n\n---\n\n**How it works:**\n- Push a tag like `v1.0.0` → workflow runs\n- GitHub injects an OIDC token (via `id-token: write`)\n- `dotnet nuget push` uses the token automatically — no API key needed\n- NuGet.org validates the token against your trusted publisher config (owner, repo, workflow, environment must all match)\n\n**Key points:**\n- The `environment: nuget` in the workflow must match what you registered on nuget.org\n- The workflow filename (`publish.yml`) must also match\n- No `--api-key` flag is needed in the push command — the OIDC token is picked up automatically by the NuGet client\n\nThe workflow file is at `.github/workflows/publish.yml` in your workspace.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"1c95b2df-49ae-4c26-a711-0e7c5f0a8195","outputTokens":226,"requestId":"D006:2D5697:34CD274:3AF375A:69FDA749"},"id":"385c8d11-bfbe-4311-b132-21014079fdd8","timestamp":"2026-05-08T09:05:21.877Z","parentId":"0b598451-4fb4-4600-a2f9-41d7ca7d1239"}
